oh well we can add that to selectors too that's not an xpath vs selectors thing selectors has intentionally avoided having such a feature because it's a perf nightmare right, i'm just saying that if that's what you're missing, it'd be easier to add it to selectors than replace selectors with xpath my :matches(...#...) proposal handles all of that a:matches(#+b) matches an a followed by a b sibling a:matches(#>b) matches an a followed by a b child 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0: when you get a result, click it, hit back, then hit "block this site" you really should log in to google anyway, it makes your results way better (disclaimer, tab and i work for google) it's not so much to allow single-pass (you already can't do that with e.g. :last-child) it's to allow you to style the document without having to do a full crawl of the entire document for each element consider *:matches(.foo) { }, for example, which would match any element if the document had a class=foo element in it for every element, you'd have to walk the entire document (modulo caching) or :matches(.foo .bar ~ .baz #) which for every element would require crawling huge parts of the dom and would be very difficult to cache efficiently 1f8387eb43f131d7c309a90a4e36b5cb: that's not such a big problem, document load is just like dynamic changes to the dom er, i had my example backwards i meant :matches(# .foo ~ .bar .baz) they don't slow the document down anywhere near as much as :matches() would :-) bbl

5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0: Both of those are perfectly compatible with CSS, we've just avoided them for performance reasons, like 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e said. The downwards/forwards restriction means you can match selectors against an element *while* parsing a document, using only the information you've already parsed. Google is your friend.  Do what Google says. 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0: That's why there isn't any inherent restriction against that sort of thing.  It's just not possible with currently-defined syntax, is all. Which isn't really a problem once the entire document is present, but it means that you can't determine if that selector matches until the entire document loads. .. 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, that's equivalent to just omitting :matches(). 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0: It's not acceptable. 5cfdf2d621b2a11df72a2e70bd2ff1a0: You want to be able to display a page *as* it loads. And preferably as complete as possible, to minimize visual jank. Those are *very* rarely used. And they do indeed slow the document down when you use them. Doesn't help.  You're still doing multiple layouts over the same tree.  Once a new selector is found to match, you have to throw away most of your progress over the subtree and start again. Because one value changing can percolate down via inheritance, etc. The problem is that people don't think of CSS as complex.  We'd prefer that the performance impact be small before adding them. s/naive/all current/

after some advice - I have a program which can accept commands over a QTcpSocket - at the moment I've got it able to process multiple commands, but one I'm attempting now is sending a log which may be appended to after the initial request. i.e. a QProcess might send additional text which I want to be added. At the moment I've got the socket being closed after it's looped through all the requests and filled them. But if I do this then the socket would be closed and there may be text appended to it afterwards only ideas I've really come up with are to either only allowed one command to be processed at a time (i.e. new connection for each one) or for it to stop processing additional commands after a request for the log comes and the log signals and slots will handle closing the socket when they're done is there a better approach I could take or is the second one acceptable? oh I guess the other question is whether a single threaded application can handle multiple QTcpSockets at once? You can't define a particular value for a slot when you connect it, can you? i.e. connect a signal that doesn't have a particular variable to a slot which does and define that variable upon connection? so everything that signal signals the slot it calls it with the variable you defined on connection? yeah - but it wasn't quite what I was after a failed qobject_cast will mean that calling .isValid on the object will be false right?

Not an easy way. http://movies.crooksandliars.com/Colbert-Foley-Messages.mov Hahaha. keithalexander: Well, so here's the story: When you replace a file (or delete it), the original data is still there on disk, albeit without an easy way of accessing it. Of course, the longer you use the disk, the greater the odds that that data--which is in unallocated blocks--will be allocated to a new file and overwritten. So various low-level data recovery techniques exist to read unallocated blocks from the disk and try to find useful data in them. http://www.google.com/search?q=data+recovery+osx&start=0&ie=utf-8&oe=utf-8&client=firefox-a&rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official However, this isn't really an easy task. tantek: Note that each wiki entry is already marked up as hAtom, so you need to ensure that each issues list has a surrounding <div class=hfeed> to segregate it Fair enough Erm, what do parses do with nested hAtom at present? Yes. But do parsers currently treat nested hentries as opaque blocks? Or will entry-title in a nested hatom override the entry-title of the main entry? They _should_ be opaque blocks But as it stands, this is undefined new behaviour c74f596e4fe95fc3bb8726dbde2031b0: Yes, I fully expect it's not been implemented that way. tantek: Err‚Ä¶ some of them do. AGENT was an ignored property for a long time, it used to be actively downplayed within this community because vcard consumers didn't support it. I've no idea what the current support make-up looks like They are sub-entities that serve/represent the main vcard In business context, the main vcard could be, for example ‚ÄòDana B. Lawyer‚Äô and her vcard contains an AGENT for ‚ÄúJoe Secretary‚Äù It is, someone who acts as an ‚Äòagent‚Äô of the main person. Agent has a lot of interesting cases We published one in the blog entry for Google's Rich Snippets. ‚ÄúGoogle‚Äù was the hCard, and the three Rich Snippet developers were AGENTs. It fits into my containers concepting a bit. For example, could you, by default, imply that the organization-name for a listed AGENT is the same as for the parent hCard? Thereby sharing it between them? There are cases where it's not: Your personal assistant could be contracted to you, not to your company, but it's a scenario/content optimization that's interesting to me at present. XFN is about social relationships Agent is an organizational relationship. Or, a representational relationship, rather Oh, that's true There's perhaps case for exploring use of AGENT in combination with XFN Here's a jump, but interesting, <a class='agent' rel='co-worker' href='http://mycompany.com/people/james-doe'>James Doe</a> Lots of stuff to document under brainstorming, anyway tantek: I find the entry template a little confusing still. Shouldn't separate issues be filed as separate entries? Rather than multiple issues in a bullet-list?

Philip`: your .addCallback() idea would i'm sure result in people taking a reference to that object and then doing really evil things with it &lt 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e> Philip`: your .addCallback() idea would i'm sure result in people taking a reference to that object and then doing really evil things with it you can keep the transaction open forever e.g. if you don't add a callback it'll never close i like the api concept though

In Twisted, the asynchronous methods return a Deferred (which indicates either a result or a soon-to-be-a-result), and you can keep it forever and do addCallback whenever, and the callback is either called immediately (if the Deferred has the result already) or later (when the result becomes available) so there's not really anything evil you can do with the object I guess it's harder in JavaScript since GC isn't immediate, so you'd have to keep all the result data just in case someone's still got a reference to the deferred result Ah, transactions sound harder too :-)

Ah, I am mistaken then. 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: Subtly different. The former could mean doing something that *can* be accessible if authors take some effort.  The latter would avoid doing that in favor of something that is, well, accessible by default. Ideally we want to avoid requiring any author interaction whatsoever to acheive good accessibility. That isn't quite possible, so instead we just minimize the amount of author interaction necessary. Got it, a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9.  ^_^ Simple, widely-attested truth - the amount of accessible content decreases exponentially with the amount of effort required. (Well, maybe not exponentially - I don't have any numbers to attest that.  But super-linear at least.) Also: people don't know how to write good @summary text.  And auto-generated @summary is useless - if it can be autogenerated by the producer, it can be auto-generated by the consumer equally well. And then the consumer *knows* that it's auto-generated and can treat it differently than custom-crafted text. It *exists* in a spec. It's not "specced" though. var updateStr = ' Last updated ' + (age < 1 ? 'today' : age.toFixed(0) + ' day' + (age.toFixed(0) == 1 ? '' : 's') + ' ago') + '.'; The problem is the toFixed(0) call.  It appears to give "NaN" as the result for any number. At least, here in Chrome. Firefox does it right. So, looks like a bug on our end. Yeah, me neither. What do you want to bet it's toFixed again? 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: Not an expert, but I think that's it.

That behavior *should* be a bug, but it's not entirely clear from the spec, because it's not well-defined how the background-properties map into the inputs to the size resolution algorithm in the Image Values spec. The intent is that saying "background-size:5px" will make the "specified size" input be a 5px by 5px square, which immediately wins and sets the concrete object size to 5px by 5px. I do need to resolve precisely where background-size sits in the size resolution order. 8c8837db54a2907cacd8633547977e33: So, background-size actually repeats most of what's in the Image Values algorithm. If you provide 0, 1, or 2 dimensions, the behavior is identical to the Image Values algorithm, with the dimensions being the "specified size". It should be the other way around, actually.  Image Values has the generic algorithm that everyone uses. But the B&B module was written before I wrote that algorithm, thus the current state of affairs. You use a gradient as a background on a 200x100 box, the gradient will be resolved into a 200x100 image. This is described by the sizing algorithm. I'm not sure what we're confusing each other over. ^_^ Yes.  But gradients have no proportions before resolution, so it instead drops down to taking the height of the sizing area. fwiw, in case anyone cares about arguing against a new HTTP verb for the ping feature: AJP 1.3 seems to assume a closed list of HTTP verbs, so minting a new one would have a non-trivial cost f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: it's a protocol that Apache speaks with Java servlet containers f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: unless I'm misreading the source of an AJP 1.3 implementation, it seems to me that AJP 1.3 communicates the HTTP verb as a single byte whose meaning has to be agreed to by both ends of the AJP pipe f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I'm not saying it is good design. I'm just saying that there's a common deployment setup with which going beyond the WebDAV set of verbs is going to be expensive http://tomcat.apache.org/connectors-doc/ajp/ajpv13a.html#method note that is says "Later version of ajp13, when used with mod_jk2, will transport additional methods, even if they are not in this list." but mod_jk2 is dead and mod_jk is what people are supposed to be using again edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: perhaps. I'm just pointing out that considering the requirements Hixie had for the access-control implementability, a new HTTP verb is on a new level of difficulty fwiw, the mechanism for encoding headers in AJP13 (I guess it's really 13 and not 1.3) is extensible I think the failure to use the same mechanism for the verb is a design bug, but software has shipped

what's AJP? ok, so it's something that would potentially be used on a server for dealing with pings. however, if you consider that adding a new HTTP verb can't be that much effort, and that any system to be set up for handling pings in the future could easily upgrade. It doesn't require all servers to be upgraded. the bigger problem with ping is getting client support oh, in that case, it might be a little more difficult ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, I don't think it's entirely pointless, but having a single centralised service might work for some system e.g. google analytics, which currently uses JS to notify the google server of certain events, could make use of ping in that way

It just needs a single centralised service which understands the PING requests, and then every web developer can make use of that service to collect data and to retrieve summaries and reports It's pointless for people to run the ping-processing software on their own servers

I want to hide/show table rows oh I was going to do like <div id="test"><tr><td>text</td></tr></div> and then change the display to none or block depending on what i wanted to do webben_ said you can't put a div inside a table webben, so give the row an id? and do like document.getelementbyid...etc on the row? so i should make some sort of getelementbyclass function, and just give the rows a class that i want to show/hide ty

jimi_: It is not possible to put a DIV as a child of TABLE. It is possible to put a DIV as a child of TD or TH. However, adding a DIV is irrelevant to the goal of hiding or showing table rows. jimi_: CSS applies to TR, TD, and TD, just as it applies to DIV. orvokki: http://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/tables.html#propdef-empty-cells and http://www.cs.tut.fi/~jkorpela/HTML/emptycells.html jimi_: I said you can't put a DIV as a child of a TABLE (which is more specific). jimi_: It's hard to say the best way to select a TR without knowing more about what you're doing. jimi_: http://www.robertnyman.com/2005/11/07/the-ultimate-getelementsbyclassname/ is just one example. jimi_: You should probably also be setting a class "hidden" and set .hidden {display: none;} in your CSS. keep the JS and CSS as decoupled as possible. also think about what happens when your CSS isn't applied it may be you need to consider adding and removing rows rather than just hiding and showing them. DARKGuy: http://del.icio.us/benjaminhawkeslewis/(X)HTML%3Atable%2BdocumentObjectModel subsume|work: It's certainly valid to put DIV inside LI. The question is whether a) assuming LI, DIV is the most appropriate markup for the subcomponents b) whether a OL or UL is semantically the most appropriate markup for the end result anyways as opposed to going where? ah, yes, that's not valid. subsume|work: Not that I'm aware off. Sounds like your problems have to do with CSS styling not markup choice. and best solved with print stylesheets http://www.alistapart.com/articles/goingtoprint/ and http://css-discuss.incutio.com/?page=PrintStylesheets
